english:
  title: The Immortal Mountains
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard of the three divine mountains upon the sea,
    Where six great tortoises bore them on their heads with difficulty,
    Yet after a thousand years their strength was spent,
    And in a single day they vanished, lost beyond recovery.

    Feng Yi and the Sea God mourned what they could not keep,
    While the assembled immortals looked on in shock and sorrow,
    As the azure waters grew distant and the clouds grew vast,
    And after wandering for years, they returned to the human realm.

    The immortal mountains' forms remain unchanged still—
    See how the jade forests and precious grasses shimmer!
    These sacred herbs are mostly the elixir of deathlessness,
    And I wish to gather them to preserve my ruddy complexion.

    But fearing the immortals despise the noise of mortals below,
    I bow my head and entreat heaven, and heaven grows miserly.
    So the goddess Kuaei carries them off into the night,
    Returning them beyond the sea, lest they linger too long
    Among the dust and debris of this world.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The three divine mountains (三神山) are legendary islands in Chinese and Korean mythology believed to float upon the sea, home to immortals and bearing wondrous plants of immortality.
  - key: ''
    value: The six tortoises (六鰲) reference the mythological supports of these floating mountains, which were said to grow weary over time.
  - key: ''
    value: Feng Yi (馮夷) is the river god, and the Sea God (海若) represents the personified sea itself.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem plays on the tension between the speaker's desire for immortality and the transience of all things, even the legendary islands of the immortals.
